\f7\b \cf9 Bimodal / Dual-Input Interfaces in Computer History\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qj\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0 \cf9 There is precedent for separating these roles in computer\'a0history\
but it has never been a topic of discussion and was basically overlooked in the 1970s.\'a0\'a0\
The 1963 Sketchpad demo by\'a0Ivan Sutherland\'a0({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RyU50qbvzQ"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RyU50qbvzQ}}) \
separated the pen\'92s input from the buttons that established\'a0points for the line.\'a0\'a0Making these roles distinct, \
separating them\'a0into\'a0two input locations that make use of use both hands, provides \
the user\'a0greater control over the vectors which is certainly why Sutherland did not place any\
buttons on the pen itself (the kind of thing our mouse does currently).\'a0 Had he\
done that, for one, he would have fewer buttons available to him.\
\
One obstacle to moving in this direction in recent times is that there is a notion \
that the more overtly mechancial-feeling a product is, like Sutherland\'92s Sketchpad, \
the less favorably it will be received by the consumer.  But in the long-term this\
will not matter.  The main issue is that there is something wrong at the moment \
or else the touchscreen devices could match the mouse-driven software \
and at the same time there would be less desire to move away from the mouse.\
That is not the case, as people often want to get away from the mouse\
but know the current touchscreen devices cannot match its cursor interactivity.\
